Universal Hamiltonians for Exponentially Long Simulation

Thomas C. Bohdanowicz Institute of Quantum Information and Matter, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA Fernando G.S.L. Brand√£o Institute of Quantum Information and Matter, California Institute of Technology, Pasadena, CA
Abstract

We construct a Hamiltonian whose dynamics simulate the dynamics of every other Hamiltonian up to exponentially long times in the system size. The Hamiltonian is time independent, local, one dimensional, and translation invariant. As a consequence, we show (under plausible computational complexity assumptions) that the circuit complexity of the unitary dynamics under this Hamiltonian grows steadily with time up to an exponential value in system size. This result makes progress on a recent conjecture by Susskind, in the context of the AdS/CFT correspondence, that the time evolution of the thermofield double state of two conformal field theories with a holographic dual has circuit complexity increasing linearly in time, up to exponential time.

1 Introduction

The notion of universality is central in science. At its core is the idea that a simple set of objects can describe the fundamental properties of a much richer class of objects. One particular successful example in physics is the use of universality in classifying phase transitions. It turns out that critical phenomena can be understood by only looking at a small set of systems and critical exponents associated to them, which are universal in the sense that they can reproduce the critical behavior of every other system [1]. A second example, which is the focus of this paper, is the study of universal quantum dynamics. The goal here is to understand and classify, in several different scenarios, which quantum dynamics can simulate any other [2]. This line of investigation is at the core of the idea of a (universal) quantum computer, which should be able to efficiently simulate the dynamics of any quantum system [3, 4]. It also naturally extends to the quantum domain the study of universality in classical dynamics, usually considered in the context of cellular automata.

There are several different notions of universality of quantum dynamics. One of the first to be considered was the notion of universal quantum gates, in which one is interested in sets of quantum gates that can approximate any unitary operator. This is a rich problem and there is a beautiful theory around it [5, 6], still with many unresolved questions. A noteworthy result is that almost any two qubit gate is universal in the sense that it (together with the ability to swap the qubits) can approximate any other unitary. Therefore, in a well defined sense, universality is the general rule for quantum gates.

Another notion concerns universal Hamiltonians. Here we are interested in identifying Hamiltonians whose dynamics can simulate any other (more precisely we can ask whether we can perform universal quantum computation with the Hamiltonian). One variant of the question is to consider sets of few-qubit interactions and classify which are universal, given the ability of switching the interactions in a time-dependent fashion. This question is closely related to the one for quantum gates and, similarly, a generic two-qubit Hamiltonian is typically universal for quantum computing [7].

Another interesting variant is to consider a fixed time-independent Hamiltonian and ask if it is universal. It is clear that the class of unitaries which can be approximated by the time evolution of a fixed Hamiltonian is rather limited (as the eigenbasis of ei‚Äãt‚ÄãHsuperscriptùëíùëñùë°ùêªe^{itH} for a fixed HùêªH is always the same). However the situation is more interesting if one allows for some form of encoding of the dynamics by preparing the initial state of the system in a suitable way. Indeed, Vollbrecht and Cirac [8] gave a construction of a time-independent and translation-invariant model which is universal for quantum computing. The desired quantum circuit to be implemented is encoded in the initial state as a particular computational basis state. Later on, Nagaj and Wocjan made refinements to this construction in [9]. In contrast to the other notions of universality, it is unclear if a typical local Hamiltonian will be universal in the sense above. Indeed apart from a few examples, it is still largely unexplored which Hamiltonians are universal for time-independent evolutions.

Circuit Complexity: An a priori unrelated question in quantum complexity theory concerns the circuit complexity of quantum dynamics. The circuit complexity of a unitary operator consists of the minimum number of two-qubit gates needed to (approximately) construct the unitary. Large complexity is a general feature of unitary operators. Indeed a simple counting argument shows that most unitaries on nùëõn qubits will have circuit complexity 2Œ©‚Äã(n)superscript2Œ©ùëõ2^{\Omega(n)} [10]. Moreover in Ref. [11] it was shown that most quantum circuits with mùëöm gates have circuit complexity at least Œ©‚Äã(m1/11)Œ©superscriptùëö111\Omega(m^{1/11}). It is much harder to prove circuit complexity lower bounds for the evolution of a fixed Hamiltonian (or even for the application of a fixed unitary many times). Indeed, proving a superpolynomial lower bound on circuit complexity for exponential long times would result in a major breakthrough in classical complexity theory (as shown in [10], it would imply that PSPACE is not contained in BQP/\textsc{BQP}/poly, which appears to be far beyond the reach of current proof techniques).

It turns out that the concept of universality naturally connects with circuit complexity. If one aims to find a unitary whose dynamics has large circuit complexity, it would be natural to consider one whose time evolution is universal, capable of simulating any other evolution (with a reasonable overhead). Indeed, from the result of [11], it directly follows that we can lower bound the circuit complexity of the unitary evolution of the Vollbrecht-Cirac universal Hamiltonian [8] on nùëõn qubits, for large enough time, by ncsuperscriptùëõùëên^{c}, for a constant c>0ùëê0c>0. However it is not clear how to obtain larger lower bounds (i.e. superpolynomial in nùëõn) for long times, e.g. exponential in nùëõn, even under computational complexity assumptions. This is a natural problem to consider on its own (e.g. it was considered in Ref. [12] under the name of "fast-forwarding" and connected to the time-energy uncertainty relation), but it has recently gained a renewed interest due to a possible unexpected application in the context of quantum gravity and holography, which we now briefly review.

Susskind‚Äôs Conjecture: The AdS/CFT correspondence [13] posits the equivalence between a theory of quantum gravity in Anti-de-Sitter (AdS) space (i.e. gravity with a negative cosmological constant) with d+1ùëë1d+1 dimensions (called the bulk theory) and a quantum conformal field theory (CFT) with dùëëd dimensions (called the boundary theory). This idea suggests that gravity is an emergent phenomenon (as it does not appear explicitly in the CFT description) and has become one of the most influential ideas in physics in the last twenty years. The correspondence is usually phrased as a dictionary between properties of the two theories.

Yet there is one property of the quantum gravity picture for which it is hard to find a suitable partner in the CFT picture. This is the volume of a non-traversible wormhole (or Einstein-Rosen bridge) in AdS space connecting two boundary CFTs. One can argue that the volume of the wormhole will grow linearly with time up to exponential time [14]. But most of the traditionally considered physical properties of the CFT (which usually involve only few-body operators) will equilibrate much sooner (on the timescale of the scrambling time). One property of the CFT system which does seem to have the same behaviour as the volume of the wormhole is the circuit complexity of the joint quantum state111Analogously to the circuit complexity of a unitary, the circuit complexity of a state is the minimum number of two-qubit gates (from a given universal set of gates) needed to (approximately) create the state. of the two CFTs associated with the boundary of the wormhole (given by the time evolution of the so-called ‚Äòthermofield double state‚Äô (TDS), which at infinite temperature reduces to a maximally entangled state of the two CFTs). Indeed, in analogy with the behavior of the wormhole volume, we expect the circuit complexity of the state to grow linearly with time up to exponential in the size of the system, at which point it has to saturate. Then at recursion times (which is doubly exponential in system size) the circuit complexity will have sharp oscillation before stabilizing again at an exponential value. Such a connection prompted Susskind to conjecture that the circuit complexity of the CFT state is the dual property of the volume of the wormhole.

Although fascinating, Susskind‚Äôs proposal is still somewhat speculative; it is an interesting and challenging task to make it more concrete. Progress was made by Aaronson and Susskind [15]. They considered a toy model of the problem for which concrete results about the circuit complexity could be established. Let VùëâV describe one step of the time evolution of the CFT. The CFT thermofield double state (at infinite temperature and regularizing the theory to have finite dimension NùëÅN) after tùë°t time steps is given by

A natural open question is whether one can prove something similar for the evolution of the CFT. Short of that, can we get closer to this goal? For example, can we find a local Hamiltonian whose evolution can replace the step function of the cellular automaton in the Aaronson-Susskind reasoning?

1.2 Sketch of Construction

The construction of our circuit universal Hamiltonian family (CUHF) that proves Theorem 3 makes use of the concept of a Hamiltonian Quantum Cellular Automaton (HQCA), as described by Nagaj and Wocjan in [9]. The formal definition of an HQCA is as follows:

Definition 6.

A Hamiltonian Quantum Cellular Automaton (HQCA) is a local, time-independent, translation-invariant Hamiltonian HùêªH on a lattice of qudits which carries out quantum computation via the following sequence of steps:

  1. 1.

    The input of the computation as well as information describing the computation to be performed (which is described by some unitary operator UùëàU) is encoded in the state of the qudits.

  2. 2.

    The qudits undergo continuous time evolution under HùêªH for some time tùë°t.

  3. 3.

    A simple basis state measurement on a subset of the qudits collapses, with high probability, the state of the whole system to one where an appropriate subset of the qudits contains the desired output of the quantum computation.

Such a Hamiltonian HùêªH is termed a cellular automaton because the local terms which sum up to make HùêªH can usually be thought of as transitions between different basis states for a local part of the lattice, which themselves correspond to reversible transition rules of some classical cellular automaton. This will be evident in the description of our construction.

Our CUHF {Hm}m‚àà‚Ñïsubscriptsubscriptùêªùëöùëö‚Ñï\{H_{m}\}_{m\in\mathbb{N}} will actually be a family of universal HQCA on a 1Dùê∑D chain of mùëöm qudits, which satisfy the following properties in addition to those in the definition above:

  • ‚Ä¢

    The local qudit dimension is constant.

  • ‚Ä¢

    A quantum circuit UùëàU with Cùê∂C gates acting on NùëÅN qubits can be applied tùë°t times through time evolution via Hamiltonian HmsubscriptùêªùëöH_{m} on a chain of m=poly‚Äã(N,C,log‚Å°t)ùëöpolyùëÅùê∂ùë°m={\rm{poly}}(N,C,\log{t}) qudits.

The starting point of our construction is that of Nagaj and Wocjan [9], which produces a 1Dùê∑D CUHF with constant local qudit dimension d=20ùëë20d=20, for which the size of the chain scales as m=poly‚Äã(N,C)ùëöpolyùëÅùê∂m={\rm{poly}}(N,C). A version of this construction is described in detail in section 2, where we also identify and highlight some important features of their construction that are essential to preserve in our eventual final construction 333E.g., the definition and consequences of having a uniquely orthogonally generated set of states for an HQCA, see section 2.8.

We build an HQCA which only encodes UùëàU into the input state and a number tùë°t encoded in binary, but which is able to apply UùëàU repeatedly up to tùë°t times after waiting for a time t‚Ä≤=poly‚Äã(N,C,t)superscriptùë°‚Ä≤polyùëÅùê∂ùë°t^{\prime}={\rm{poly}}(N,C,t) [18]. Therefore the size of the system needed for the simulation is only m=poly‚Äã(N,log‚Å°t)ùëöpolyùëÅùë°m={\rm{poly}}(N,\log{t}). In the following sections, we proceed to augment Nagaj-Wocjan construction [9] step by step to add in more functionality until we achieve the desired m=poly‚Äã(N,log‚Å°t)ùëöpolyùëÅùë°m={\rm{poly}}(N,\log{t}) scaling for the simulation size.

The innovations which allow us to obtain our final construction dictate the organization of the remainder of the paper:

  1. 1.

    The Nagaj-Wocjan construction can only apply its encoded unitary UùëàU once. So, first, we modify the Nagaj-Wocjan construction so that when the HQCA reaches its end state where UùëàU has been applied, it can undergo transitions to ‚Äòreset‚Äô itself and allow for another application of UùëàU without undoing the original application of UùëàU. This basically has the effect of allowing the Nagaj-Wocjan construction to run over and over again rather than just once. This is described in Section 3.

  2. 2.

    Next, we augment the construction to include a binary clock in the qudit chain which counts the number of times that UùëàU has been applied. This allows states of the chain with different numbers of UùëàU applications to be orthogonal so that they can be distinguished by a simple measurement. Binary clock constructions of a similar nature also appear in [19, 20, 21], in the context of proving hardness/uncomputability results for the ground-energy/gap of translation-invariant models. This is described in Section 4.

  3. 3.

    Finally, we augment the construction with the addition of a target register that allows one to specify a certain desired number of applications of UùëàU which is stored in the start state. Once the clock has counted this number of applications of UùëàU, the HQCA continues evolving forward in time similarly to the way in which it did before, but it no longer makes any applications of UùëàU to the qubits. This allows one to have complete control over how many times UùëàU is applied to the qubits, and is crucial to being able to guarantee that after waiting a reasonable amount of time, performing a simple measurement on a subset of the chain is likely to yield a state with the desired number of applications of UùëàU. This is described in Section 5.

The main challenge in achieving each of these results was to carefully engineer transition rules such that starting from the appropriate start state, for every state that can be obtained from the start state through application of transition rules, exactly one forward transition rule and one reverse transition rule is applicable to that state. This guarantees that the sequence of states obtained from the start state through application of the HQCA transition rules can map directly onto position eigenstates of a single particle on a chain, so that the analysis of the time evolution under the HQCA reduces to that of a single particle continuous-time quantum walk on a line (see Sections 2.8 and 5.5).

2 Construction I: Applying UùëàU Once

We begin with the modest goal of applying UùëàU to our qubits once (x=1ùë•1x=1) using the time evolution of a simple time-independent and translation-invariant Hamiltonian, where the sequence of gates that implements UùëàU is stored in the start state of the qudit chain that we embed our qubits into for the simulation. The construction described in this section only differs from the d=20ùëë20d=20 HQCA construction of Nagaj and Wocjan [9] in notation (and only slightly at that). We do, however, formalize and elaborate on some of the essential ideas underlying the success and utility of their construction which will be important in subsequent sections when we expand their construction, the most important of which being the definition of what it means for a sequences of quantum states to be ‚Äòuniquely orthogonally generated‚Äô by a sequence of transition rules of an HQCA (see Section 2.7). The construction described in this section will be referred to as ‚Äòconstruction I‚Äô throughout the rest of the paper.

The universal gate set we will use to describe a quantum circuit for UùëàU is ùí¢={W,S,I}ùí¢ùëäùëÜùêº\mathcal{G}=\{W,S,I\} where each gate acts on a local pair of left and right qubits and

  • ‚Ä¢

    WùëäW is a controlled rotation by œÄ/2ùúã2\pi/2 about the yùë¶y-axis of the Bloch sphere (where the left qubit always controls the right)

  • ‚Ä¢

    SùëÜS is the two-qubit swap gate

  • ‚Ä¢

    IùêºI is shorthand for the two-qubit identity gate I‚äóItensor-productùêºùêºI\otimes I.

We note that because all of these gates leave the state |00‚ü©ket00\left|00\right\rangle invariant, to use these gates to simulate the application of an arbitrary UùëàU on a state of the form |0n‚ü©ketsuperscript0ùëõ\left|0^{n}\right\rangle, some number of qubits in the |1‚ü©ket1\left|1\right\rangle state must be provided in order to simulate gates that act non-trivially on the |0‚ü©ket0\left|0\right\rangle state. This overhead is polynomial in the number of gates that UùëàU would have in a circuit using a more traditional gateset, so we ignore it and assume that the state that our gates act on has the correct number of qubits in |1‚ü©ket1\left|1\right\rangle states for the simulation to proceed.

For the convenience of the construction, the way that UùëàU breaks down into a sequence of gates from ùí¢ùí¢\mathcal{G} will be as follows: we write the unitary as a gate sequence from ùí¢ùí¢\mathcal{G} in the form

U=(UK,1‚Äã‚Ä¶‚ÄãUK,N‚àí1)‚ÄãI‚ÄãI‚Äã(UK‚àí1,1‚Äã‚Ä¶‚ÄãUK‚àí1,N‚àí1)‚ÄãI‚ÄãI‚Äã‚ãØ‚ÄãI‚ÄãI‚Äã(U1,1‚Äã‚Ä¶‚ÄãU1,N‚àí1)‚ÄãI.ùëàsubscriptùëàùêæ1‚Ä¶subscriptùëàùêæùëÅ1ùêºùêºsubscriptùëàùêæ11‚Ä¶subscriptùëàùêæ1ùëÅ1ùêºùêº‚ãØùêºùêºsubscriptùëà11‚Ä¶subscriptùëà1ùëÅ1ùêº\displaystyle U=(U_{K,1}\dots U_{K,N-1})II(U_{K-1,1}\dots U_{K-1,N-1})II\cdots II(U_{1,1}\dots U_{1,N-1})I. (6)

Here we say that UùëàU is expressed as KùêæK rounds of N‚àí1ùëÅ1N-1 gates from ùí¢ùí¢\mathcal{G}. Note that the use of the term ‚Äòround‚Äô of gates differs here from the usual usage. Normally, a round of gates from some gate set is some tensor product of m‚â§NùëöùëÅm\leq N single or two-qubit gates with the property that each of the NùëÅN qubits has exactly one gate acting on it (identity counted as a gate). This allows the number of rounds making up UùëàU to count the time complexity of applying the circuit. This is not true of our rounds. The gate Uk,m‚ààùí¢subscriptùëàùëòùëöùí¢U_{k,m}\in\mathcal{G} is a two qubit gate acting on qubits mùëöm and m+1ùëö1m+1. So, two successive gates in a round, Uk,msubscriptùëàùëòùëöU_{k,m} and Uk,m+1subscriptùëàùëòùëö1U_{k,m+1} will possibly each act non-trivially on qubit m+1ùëö1m+1. Thus, the number of rounds, KùêæK, in our circuit description of UùëàU will in general under-count the depth or time complexity of applying UùëàU as written, but it will undercount at most by a factor of NùëÅN. The reason we write our circuit this way is for the convenience of constructing our desired HQCA. For ease of discussion, we will use the term depth of UùëàU to refer to the numbe of rounds, KùêæK, in the above sense rather than the traditional sense.

Notice also that in the above description, each round of gates is padded with an additional IùêºI on either side, except for the final round which does not have an IùêºI on the left side. The reason for this is that it makes the construction of our desired HQCA more convenient, and will be explained below. With the above convention for describing UùëàU in terms of ùí¢ùí¢\mathcal{G}, a unitary UùëàU of depth KùêæK acting on NùëÅN qubits has a circuit sequence of length K‚Äã(N+1)‚àí1ùêæùëÅ11K(N+1)-1.

2.5 Active Site

A subset of the basis states for PjsubscriptùëÉùëóP_{j} whose symbols contain directional arrows of some form, ùíúI={‚Üí,W‚Üí,I‚Üí,S‚Üí,‚óÄ,‚ä≤}subscriptùíúùêº‚Üí‚Üíùëä‚Üíùêº‚ÜíùëÜ‚óÄ‚ä≤\mathcal{A}_{I}=\{\rightarrow,\overrightarrow{W},\overrightarrow{I},\overrightarrow{S},\,\blacktriangleleft,\,\vartriangleleft\}, are called active symbols. By construction, the initial state and all states resulting from applying a sequence of transition rules to the initial state will always contain exactly one active symbol, the site at which it is located being referred to as the active site of the chain. All transition rules for the HQCA involve the propagation of the active site to a neighbouring site and/or transforming one active symbol into another. This feature will be helpful in analysing the construction below.

So, we see that applying this unique sequence of 17 forward transitions has moved the active site ‚Üí‚Üí\rightarrow from the far left of the gate sequence over the to the far right of the gate sequence (equation 56), converted the active symbol ‚Üí‚Üí\rightarrow into the active symbol ‚óÄ‚óÄ\,\blacktriangleleft which is the gate applying symbol (equation 59), which then moved back to the left applying gates to the qubits below, shifting the gate sequence a single site to the right as it went (equations 62, 65 and 68). The halfway point of an oscillation, just before the ‚Üí‚Üí\rightarrow symbol turns around to move left as ‚óÄ‚óÄ\,\blacktriangleleft (as illustrated in equation 56) is called the turning point of the oscillation.

Note that the first round of gates was applied to the work qubits during the first oscillation, no gates were applied during oscillations 2, 3, or 4, and the second round of gates was applied during the fifth oscillation, completing the application of the desired UùëàU. Whether or not a particular oscillation will apply gates to the data qubits in the second half of the oscillation depends on whether or not there is a 1 or 0 in the data qubit below the active symbol when it reaches the far right of the oscillation. We can see in equations 56 and 59, the active symbol ‚Üí‚Üí\rightarrow becomes an apply gate symbol ‚óÄ‚óÄ\,\blacktriangleleft because there is a 111 in the data register of the active site at the turning point. If there were a zero instead, which is true at the turning points of the next three oscillations, ‚Üí‚Üí\rightarrow would turn into ‚ä≤‚ä≤\,\vartriangleleft and no gates would be applied in the second half of the oscillation. This is good because the second round of gates is not yet aligned with the work qubits (see equations 68, 71 and 80), and we do not want to be applying any gates until this alignment is achieved.

So, we see that the pattern of ones and zeros in the data qubits to the right of the work qubits is simply chosen so that transition rules 4a and 4b can properly enforce that gates are only applied for the first in every N+1ùëÅ1N+1 oscillations, which is precisely when rounds of gates will properly be aligned to the work qubits that they will be applied to. The pattern of the data qubits to the left of the work qubits mirrors that on the right so that transition rules 6a and 6b can properly convert ‚óÄ‚óÄ\,\blacktriangleleft or ‚ä≤‚ä≤\,\vartriangleleft back into ‚Üí‚Üí\rightarrow at the end of the oscillation. Finally, note also that whenever we begin an oscillation that applies gates, rounds of gates that are not being applied during that round are aligned so that they are always applied to |00‚ü©ket00\left|00\right\rangle qubit states, on which the SùëÜS and WùëäW gates both act trivially. So, we see that the states on the non-work qubits in the data register remain invariant under the application of our HQCA transition rules.

Finally, after one more half oscillation (8 steps) we reach a state |œà93‚ü©ketsubscriptùúì93\left|\psi_{93}\right\rangle to which no forward transition rules apply:

(83)

Nagaj and Wocjan [9] show that by time evolving the appropriate initial state |œà0‚ü©ketsubscriptùúì0\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle encoding the desired unitary under Hamiltonian HIsubscriptùêªùêºH_{I} for time polynomial in KùêæK and NùëÅN, a simple measurement on a subset of the chain will collapse the state of the work qubits to U‚Äã|0N‚ü©ùëàketsuperscript0ùëÅU\left|0^{N}\right\rangle with high probability. We defer any run-time analysis to the end of the paper where we will present the run-time analysis for our full construction which is based on this one.

The following definition will be essential for further understanding and analyzing the time evolution generated by this Hamiltonian and those based on it later in the paper:

Definition 7.

Consider the Hilbert space of states ùíûùíû\mathcal{C} of any HQCA described in this paper. A sequence of T+1ùëá1T+1 states from ùíûùíû\mathcal{C}, {|œàt‚ü©}t=0Tsuperscriptsubscriptketsubscriptùúìùë°ùë°0ùëá\left\{\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle\right\}_{t=0}^{T}, is called Uniquely Orthogonally Generated (UOG) by sequence of forward transition rules of the HQCA, ùíÆùíÆ\mathcal{S} (which has length TùëáT), if the two following conditions are satisfied:

  1. 1.

    The states {|œàt‚ü©}t=0Tsuperscriptsubscriptketsubscriptùúìùë°ùë°0ùëá\left\{\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle\right\}_{t=0}^{T} are each a product state over all sites and registers aside from the work qubits, and are mutually orthogonal (thus the states differ in at least one site of the chain)

  2. 2.

    For each state |œàt<T‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìùë°ùëá\left|\psi_{t<T}\right\rangle, there is exactly one forward transition rule that can be applied to the state, and the application of this rule yields the state |œàt+1‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìùë°1\left|\psi_{t+1}\right\rangle

It is clear from the illustration of a single right-moving oscillation as in the example above that the sequence of intermediate states of the chain throughout a right-moving oscillation is UOG by the sequence of transitions described above.

We will name the unique sequence of forward transitions that takes the initial state of the chain, |œà0‚ü©ketsubscriptùúì0\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle, to the final state |œàTI‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìsubscriptùëáùêº\left|\psi_{T_{I}}\right\rangle ùíØI‚àà‚Ñ±ITIsubscriptùíØùêºsubscriptsuperscript‚Ñ±subscriptùëáùêºùêº\mathcal{T}_{I}\in\mathcal{F}^{T_{I}}_{I}. This sequence {|œàt‚ü©}t=0TIsuperscriptsubscriptketsubscriptùúìùë°ùë°0subscriptùëáùêº\left\{\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle\right\}_{t=0}^{T_{I}} is UOG by ùíØIsubscriptùíØùêº\mathcal{T}_{I}. This is easily seen from the fact that for each individual right-moving oscillation, the set of transitions that implements it is unique, and for each successive oscillation the sets of intermediate states are orthogonal to those of all other oscillations because the program sequence starts at a different position in each oscillation. Thus, every state in the sequence {|œàt‚ü©}t=0TIsuperscriptsubscriptketsubscriptùúìùë°ùë°0subscriptùëáùêº\left\{\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle\right\}_{t=0}^{T_{I}} is orthonormal to all others in the sequence. Further, for each state in {|œàt‚ü©}t=0TIsuperscriptsubscriptketsubscriptùúìùë°ùë°0subscriptùëáùêº\left\{\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle\right\}_{t=0}^{T_{I}}, only one forward transition can be applied at each step because this was true of the individual right-moving oscillations. Thus {|œàt‚ü©}t=0TIsuperscriptsubscriptketsubscriptùúìùë°ùë°0subscriptùëáùêº\left\{\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle\right\}_{t=0}^{T_{I}} is UOG by ùíØIsubscriptùíØùêº\mathcal{T}_{I}.

Now we can see the benefit of the UOG property. The fact that the sequence of states {|œàt‚ü©}t=0TIsuperscriptsubscriptketsubscriptùúìùë°ùë°0subscriptùëáùêº\left\{\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle\right\}_{t=0}^{T_{I}} is UOG by ùíØIsubscriptùíØùêº\mathcal{T}_{I} allows one to be able to think of the set of states |œàt‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìùë°\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle as the set of positions of a particle on a line, so HIsubscriptùêªùêºH_{I} becomes

3 Construction II - Applying UùëàU More Than Once

What is needed in order to apply UùëàU more than once? In the construction that has been made so far, we see that after applying UùëàU once to the state of the work qubits, the state of the HQCA reaches a state for which no forward transition rules can be applied. In the language of the quantum walk, the particle has reached the end of the line, so all it can do is turn around and walk the other way, which would undo the application of UùëàU to the work qubits. So under arbitrarily long time evolution UùëàU will never be applied to the work qubits more than once. To apply UùëàU twice, we would desire to be in a state like the start state in Eq. (53) except with UùëàU already applied to the work qubits. So, if there were some way of taking the end state in Eq. (83) and then somehow move the program sequence back to its starting position without undoing the application of UùëàU to the work qubits, then we could apply forward transition rules to apply UùëàU again. Here, we modify the construction to allow this. We proceed by adding a new set of local basis states to the program register Hilbert states and transition rules that will allow the program sequence to reset itself without undoing the application of UùëàU. We will refer to the construction described in this section as ‚Äòconstruction II‚Äô.

3.1 Hilbert Space

The following changes are made to the local program register Hilbert space: we add the new basis states represented by symbols {W‚Üê,S‚Üê,I‚Üê,‚ä≥,‚Üê,‚Ü∫}‚Üêùëä‚ÜêùëÜ‚Üêùêº‚ä≥‚Üê‚Ü∫\{\overleftarrow{W},\overleftarrow{S},\overleftarrow{I},\,\vartriangleright,\leftarrow,\,\circlearrowleft\,\}. The length of the chain is increased by two sites.

4 Construction III: Binary Clock Construction

We would like to modify Construction II so that by applying forward transition rules, all of the uniquely obtained states of the chain at each step, |œàt‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìùë°\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle, are mutually orthogonal, and as a particular consequence, states of the chain where the work qubits have had UùëàU applied a different number of times will be orthogonal, and can be distinguished by doing a computational basis state measurement on a subset of the chain that excludes the work qubits. We will accomplish this by further modifying the construction in the previous section. First, we give an overview of how the clock itself should work, then we describe how to implement its control and integration into our existing construction, and then we will prove its correctness. Similar binary clock constructions appear in [19, 20, 21].

4.3 Clock Schematic and Update Algorithm

Here we describe a simple algorithm for updating a binary counter which will be implemented in our HQCA transition rules. The idea is the following: The clock register, consisting of LùêøL sites, can store a binary number of up to L‚àí1ùêø1L-1 digits long. Numbers with n<Lùëõùêøn<L significant digits will be stored in the nùëõn rightmost sites of the clock register via the 00 and 111 states, and the remaining L‚àínùêøùëõL-n sites will all be in the state 00 except for the first register which will always be ‚àô‚àô\>\>\centerdot\>. Significant bits will increase from right to left, so, for example, the binary representation of the number 6, in our clock, will look like ‚àô‚ÄÖ0‚Äã‚Ä¶‚Äã00000110‚àôabsent‚ÄÖ0‚Ä¶00000110\>\>\centerdot\>0...00000110.

Given any binary number represented in this form, we can use the following schematic algorithm for incrementing it by 111:

  • ‚Ä¢

    A) Initialize a ‚Äòpointer‚Äô which starts sitting underneath the least significant bit.

  • ‚Ä¢

    B) If the least significant bit is 0, change it to a 1, end

  • ‚Ä¢

    C) If the least significant bit is 1, and the next bit is 0, update both bits 10‚Üí01‚Üí100110\to 01, end

  • ‚Ä¢

    D) Otherwise, the first two bits are 111111. In this case, move the pointer to the left, bit by bit, until it encounters a 111 bit whose next most significant bit is a 00. When it is found, update these two bits 01‚Üí10‚Üí011001\to 10. Move the pointer back to the right, bit by bit, flipping all of the less significant 111 bits to 00 as it passes, until it is back under the least significant bit, end.

  • ‚Ä¢

    E) If the number being incremented is ‚àô‚ÄÖ11‚Äã‚Ä¶‚Äã1‚àôabsent11‚Ä¶1\>\>\centerdot\>11...1, then the pointer halts when it reaches the most significant 111, as this number can not be incremented further.

In our construction, the C‚ÄãPùê∂ùëÉCP register is where the pointer that scans through and increments the clock registers will live. Generally, when the clock is not being incremented, the C‚ÄãPùê∂ùëÉCP register will be in the state ‚àô‚àô‚Ä¶‚àôX\>\>\centerdot\>\>\>\centerdot\>...\>\>\centerdot\>X. This indicates that the ‚Äòpointer‚Äô is underneath the least significant bit of the clock, and is inactive, XùëãX. The ‚àô‚àô\>\>\centerdot\> symbol underneath all of the other bits simply indicates the absence of the clock pointer. When the clock pointer is scanning to the left, looking for a 111 bit whose next most significant bit is a 00, it will be in state LùêøL and will hop right past the ‚àô‚àô\>\>\centerdot\> symbols until it encounters this configuration in the clock register. Then it updates the clock bits according to the algorithm above, the pointer in state LùêøL transitions to a pointer in state RùëÖR, and will now start scanning back to the right, flipping the less significant 111 bits it encounters along the way to 00 bits. Once it reaches the least significant bit, the clock pointer transitions to the Cùê∂C state to indicate that the clock update is complete, and then back to the XùëãX state, in which it will stay until it is once again called upon to increment the clock.

4.5 Active Site

In analyzing the correctness of the above transition rules for achieving our goals, it will again be useful to make use of the concept of the active site and active symbol. In our augmented construction, there will again only ever be exactly one active symbol in the state, which will indicate the active site. But this time, the active symbol can either be in the program register or the clock pointer register, depending on whether or not the clock is being updated. The set of active symbols is now the union of the active symbols for the PùëÉP and C‚ÄãPùê∂ùëÉCP registers: ùíú=ùíúP‚à™ùíúC‚ÄãPùíúsubscriptùíúùëÉsubscriptùíúùê∂ùëÉ\mathcal{A}=\mathcal{A}_{P}\cup\mathcal{A}_{CP}, with ùíúP={‚Üê,‚Üí,W‚Üê,S‚Üê,I‚Üê,W‚Üí,S‚Üí,I‚Üí,‚ä≤,‚óÄ,‚ä≥,‚áä}subscriptùíúùëÉ‚Üê‚Üí‚Üêùëä‚ÜêùëÜ‚Üêùêº‚Üíùëä‚ÜíùëÜ‚Üíùêº‚ä≤‚óÄ‚ä≥‚áä\mathcal{A}_{P}=\{\leftarrow,\rightarrow,\overleftarrow{W},\overleftarrow{S},\overleftarrow{I},\overrightarrow{W},\overrightarrow{S},\overrightarrow{I},\,\vartriangleleft,\,\blacktriangleleft,\,\vartriangleright,\downdownarrows\} and ùíúC‚ÄãP={L,R,C}subscriptùíúùê∂ùëÉùêøùëÖùê∂\mathcal{A}_{CP}=\{L,R,C\}. Transition rules 14 and 21 describe the passing of the active symbol between the program and clock pointer registers. It is still true that every single transition rule describes the moving of an active symbol from one site to a neighbouring site and/or the conversion of one kind of active symbol into another, which is essential for our sequence of states to be UOG and for the dynamics of the HQCA to map to a quantum walk on a line.

5 Construction IV: Deterministic Selection of xùë•x in time poly(x,Nùë•ùëÅx,N)

Now we augment construction III so that a particular number xùë•x of applications of UùëàU can be selected to be applied to the work qubits, and we can obtain the state where this has happened more or less deterministically by time evolving for a time polynomial in xùë•x and NùëÅN. To do this, we build in a new register that holds the number of desired applications xùë•x in binary form, and once the number in the clock register reaches xùë•x, forward transitions are modified so that although the quantum walk continues forward, gates are no longer applied to data qubits, so there is some T<FùëáùêπT<F such that for all |œàt>T‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìùë°ùëá\left|\psi_{t>T}\right\rangle, the work qubits will always have Uxsuperscriptùëàùë•U^{x} applied to them.

5.4 Discussion

Here‚Äôs a brief outline of how this modified construction with these new transition rules works:

  • ‚Ä¢

    Transition rules 22-30 implement a new part of the clock update phase by giving it a new function at the end: when the clock pointer has finished updating the clock and is in Cùê∂C mode, it then begins a second sweep to the left in C‚Üê‚Üêùê∂\overleftarrow{C} mode, comparing the number stored in the clock to the number stored in the target register bit by bit

  • ‚Ä¢

    If the clock pointer discovers bits that do not match, it turns into C‚ÄãXùê∂ùëãCX mode, moves back to the right, and the active symbol moves back up to the program layer to begin the next unitary application as normal in construction III

  • ‚Ä¢

    If the clock pointer in C‚Üê‚Üêùê∂\overleftarrow{C} mode determines that the clock and target registers match, it continues moving left until it reaches the left end of the chain, and this causes the clock pointer to transition to R√ósuperscriptùëÖR^{\times} mode

  • ‚Ä¢

    Once the the clock pointer has transitioned to R√ósuperscriptùëÖR^{\times} mode, all future active symbols will have the √ó\times symbol attached and obey transition rules 31-50, which identically mimic transition rules 1-20 of construction I‚ÄãI‚ÄãIùêºùêºùêºIII, but are modified slightly so that a unitary is never applied to the work qubits ever again (the presence of the √ó\times symbol on all active symbols indicates this), and now the clock pointer (operating in an identical fashion to how it did in construction I‚ÄãI‚ÄãIùêºùêºùêºIII, without a phase where it compares to a target register) treats the the second clock register C‚Äã2ùê∂2C2 as the clock register.

At this point, based on our in depth analysis of construction III, it is easy to check that the sequence of states generated by forward transition rules 1‚àí501501-50 is UOG by the appropriate sequence of unique forward transitions. The outcome, then, is that the Hamiltonian HI‚ÄãVsubscriptùêªùêºùëâH_{IV} based on transition rules 1-50 implements a quantum walk on a line whose length is l=exp‚Äã(N,K)ùëôexpùëÅùêæl={\rm{exp}}(N,K) (the length of the line for constructions HI‚ÄãI‚ÄãIsubscriptùêªùêºùêºùêºH_{III} and HI‚ÄãVsubscriptùêªùêºùëâH_{IV} is exponential because the clock can count up to a time exp‚Äã(N,K)expùëÅùêæ{\rm{exp}}(N,K)). Once the quantum walk has proceeded far enough for UùëàU to have been applied to the work qubits xùë•x times (this distance is poly‚Äã(x,N,K)polyùë•ùëÅùêæ{\rm{poly}}(x,N,K)), the quantum walk can continue forward for exp‚Äã(N,K)expùëÅùêæ{\rm{exp}}(N,K) more steps without ever changing the state of the data and clock registers ever again. We complete the analysis of the construction below by proving that we only need to run the simulation for a time poly‚Äã(x,N,K)polyùë•ùëÅùêæ{\rm{poly}}(x,N,K) in order to be able to do a simple measurement on the chain that will collapse the state of the work qubits to one where Uxsuperscriptùëàùë•U^{x} has been applied with high probability.

5.5 Run-Time Analysis

Here we prove that after running construction I‚ÄãVùêºùëâIV with an appropriate input state for a time œÑ=poly‚Äã(x,N,K)ùúèpolyùë•ùëÅùêæ\tau={\rm{poly}}(x,N,K), a computational basis measurement on the clock register will return the result that xùë•x is stored in the clock register (and therefore Uxsuperscriptùëàùë•U^{x} has been applied to the work qubits) with high probability.

We now consider the consequences of this lemma for the run-time of our simulation. The length of the chain that the states |œàt‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìùë°\left|\psi_{t}\right\rangle of the simulator map onto position eigenstates |t‚ü©ketùë°\left|t\right\rangle of is l=exp‚Äã(N,K)ùëôexpùëÅùêæl={{\rm{exp}}}(N,K). Then by setting œÑ‚àó=poly‚Äã(l)superscriptùúèpolyùëô\tau^{*}={\rm{poly}}(l) appropriately, and picking a uniformly random time between 00 and œÑ‚àósuperscriptùúè\tau^{*}, we will succeed in applying Uxsuperscriptùëàùë•U^{x} to the work qubits with probability p‚àó‚â•1‚àí1/exp‚Äã(poly‚Äã(N,K))superscriptùëù11exppolyùëÅùêæp^{*}\geq 1-1/{\rm{exp}}({\rm{poly}}(N,K)). For all states |œàt>(1‚àíF)‚Äãl‚ü©ketsubscriptùúìùë°1ùêπùëô\left|\psi_{t>(1-F)l}\right\rangle, which have had Uxsuperscriptùëàùë•U^{x} applied to the work qubits, the clock register will hold the number xùë•x which was originally set in the target register. So we only need to do a computational basis measurement on the clock register and find it in the state holding the binary number xùë•x to know that we‚Äôve succeeded.

Note that if we would like to simulate the application of unitary Uxsuperscriptùëàùë•U^{x} for x=poly‚Äã(N)ùë•polyùëÅx={\rm{poly}}(N), the above strategy does not actually seem very helpful: because l=exp‚Äã(poly‚Äã(N,K))ùëôexppolyùëÅùêæl={\rm{exp}}({\rm{poly}}(N,K)) is exponential, we need to wait for, on average, exponential time to guarantee high success probability even though we‚Äôre simulating something that should only take polynomial time. This can easily be fixed. By modifying the start state of the simulator, |œà0‚ü©ketsubscriptùúì0\left|\psi_{0}\right\rangle, so that the ‚àô‚àô\>\>\centerdot\> symbol in the target register is far enough to the right, one can exponentially reduce lùëôl. This is because once the target register starts functioning as a clock (after Uxsuperscriptùëàùë•U^{x} has been applied), the length of the remaining distance the particle can travel is exponential in the number of sites to the right of the ‚àô‚àô\>\>\centerdot\> symbol in the target register. The end state is not reached until the target register has counted up to the largest number that it can. So, one can place the ‚àô‚àô\>\>\centerdot\> at the appropriate site (say, 3 sites to the left of the most significant digit of the number xùë•x stored in the target register) so that lùëôl will be polynomial in NùëÅN, but will also be large enough relative to xùë•x so that one only needs œÑ‚àósuperscriptùúè\tau^{*} to be polynomial to achieve a high rate of success. Note, however, that in this scenario, the probability of success will only be inverse polynomially close to unity rather than exponentially.

Finally, we mention that from the start state defined in equation (76), it is actually possible to apply reverse transitions to this start state which allows you to start running a ‚Äòclock check and update‚Äô phase in reverse using the reverse of transition rules 21, 25 and 20 (if the target register‚Äôs least significant bit is 1), or rules 21, 27, 23, 24 and 20 (if the target register‚Äôs least significant bit is 0). However, it is easy to check that in either case, only one unique sequence of no more than 3‚ÄãL3ùêø3L reverse transitions can be applied to this state before reaching a state from which no further reverse transitions can be made. Thus the effect on run-time analysis is insignificant.
